  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why isn't my toilet tank filling up with water?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why your toilet tank isn't filling up with water. Here are some common issues and potential solutions:\n\n1. **Shut-off Valve**: Check if the water supply valve, usually located on the wall behind the toilet, is open. If it\u2019s partially or fully closed, turn it counterclockwise to open it fully.\n\n2. **Float Ball or Float Cup**: If the float is set too low, it may stop the tank from filling properly. Adjust the float arm or cup to allow more water to enter the tank. The float should be set so the tank fills to the level indicated inside it.\n\n3. **Fill Valve**: The fill valve (or ballcock) might be malfunctioning. Debris can clog it, or it may be worn out. Cleaning or replacing the fill valve can often solve the problem.\n\n4. **Clogged Inlet Holes**: The inlet holes located under the rim of the toilet bowl might be clogged with mineral deposits, reducing water flow. Cleaning these holes can improve water flow.\n\n5. **Damaged or Broken Fill Tube**: Ensure the fill tube, which directs water into the overflow tube, is properly attached and not damaged.\n\n6. **Low Water Pressure**: If your home has low water pressure, it might affect the toilet's ability to fill. Check if other faucets are also experiencing low pressure.\n\n7. **Float Valve Issues**: If the float valve is stuck or damaged, it may prevent the float from functioning correctly. Inspect the float valve and replace it if necessary.\n\n8. **Leaking Flapper**: A leaking flapper can cause water to drain out of the tank, preventing it from filling. Check for leaks and replace the flapper if needed.\n\nIf you've checked these issues and the problem persists, it may be best to call a plumber to diagnose and fix the problem.",
